## The OpenMRS POA&M — Current State and Management Disciplines

The OpenMRS POA&M at Day 78 has 10 open items, 5 items closed during Q1 monitoring, and 2 new items added from Q1 monitoring findings. Working through the management disciplines for this specific POA&M:

---

### Timeline Management — When Deadlines Are Missed or Need Revision

The original POA&M was built with target dates established at authorization. Twelve items; twelve deadlines. Some were met. Some required revision. The revision discipline is where POA&M management most clearly differentiates genuine governance from compliance decoration.

**The wrong way to handle a deadline revision:** Update the target date in the POA&M to a new date without documenting why the original date was missed and what is different about the new commitment.

**The right way:** A deadline revision requires a formal revision entry in the POA&M item that documents: (1) why the original deadline was not met — specifically, what obstacle was encountered; (2) what has changed that makes the new deadline achievable — resources secured, scope clarified, dependency resolved; and (3) whether the missed deadline requires AO notification per the authorization conditions.

**Example — POA&M Item 001 (CP-2 Clinical Downtime Procedures):**

The 90-day authorization condition deadline was AT RISK at the Day 73 quarterly report — 12 days remaining, one unresponsive clinical leadership participant. If the Milestone 3 clinical leadership approval meeting is delayed and the deadline is missed, the revision entry would document:

*Original deadline:* [authorization date + 90 days]
*Deadline missed because:* Clinical leadership meeting originally scheduled for [date] was postponed by [name, role] due to [specific operational conflict — e.g., unplanned patient care emergency requiring full clinical leadership attention on scheduled meeting date].
*Revised deadline:* [original deadline + 14 days]
*Basis for revised deadline:* Clinical leadership meeting rescheduled for [new date] — all three required participants confirmed. Milestones 3 and 4 achievable within 14-day extension.
*AO notification:* Yes — missed authorization condition deadline, per Condition 3. AO notified [date]. AO acknowledged extension on [date].
*Compensating control during extension period:* Existing paper-based downtime procedure reference cards (Day 54 implementation) remain in place.

This revision entry creates an accountable record: what happened, why, what is different, and who knows. An AO reviewing this entry understands the delay was a specific operational disruption, not organizational indifference to the condition.

**Timeline revision thresholds for AO notification:**

Not every deadline revision requires AO notification. The classification:

- Low severity item, first revision, ≤30 days: Document in POA&M, notify Health IT Manager. No AO notification required.
- Low severity item, second revision or >30 days: Document in POA&M with detailed rationale. AO notification in next quarterly report.
- Moderate severity item, any revision: AO notification within 5 business days.
- Authorization condition item, any revision: AO notification within 24 hours.

