## What the POA&M Reveals About Security Program Health

Beyond the individual item management, the POA&M as a whole reveals the health of the security program through patterns that quarterly AO review should examine:

*Are items being added faster than they are being closed?* If the POA&M grows every quarter — new items from monitoring consistently outnumbering closures — the security program may not have sufficient remediation capacity, or the continuous monitoring program is generating findings that the organization lacks resources to address. Both are governance signals that require AO attention, not just ISSO attention.

*Are the same control families repeatedly generating new items?* If access control findings appear in every quarterly monitoring cycle, the root cause may not be individual misconfiguration events — it may be an organizational process that consistently produces access control gaps. The right response is to address the underlying process, not to add individual findings to the POA&M indefinitely.

*Are items being formally accepted or silently deferred?* A healthy POA&M closes items through remediation or formal acceptance. Items that age indefinitely without either represent decision avoidance — the organization is neither fixing the gap nor taking formal responsibility for accepting it. This pattern is what auditors and assessors look for as an indicator that the security program's accountability mechanisms are not functioning.

