## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

The POA&M aging problem — items acknowledged but never resolved — is at the heart of many of the largest healthcare breaches that OCR has investigated and settled.

The **2019 Premera Blue Cross settlement ($6.85 million)** — referenced in Day 67 in the context of authorization conditions without verification standards — had a POA&M dimension that is directly relevant here. The OCR investigation found that a 2012 risk analysis had identified vulnerabilities in Premera's systems. Those vulnerabilities were not fully remediated. The 2014 breach that exposed 11 million individuals' data exploited some of those same vulnerabilities.

The gap between the 2012 risk analysis identification and the 2014 breach is approximately two years of POA&M items that were acknowledged but not driven to closure or formal acceptance. The organization knew about the gaps. They were documented. They were not fixed, and they were not formally accepted with compensating controls — they aged in a POA&M until an attacker exploited them.

This is the governing lesson of POA&M management: the POA&M does not make the organization safer by itself. The safety comes from the remediation decisions and the formal acceptance decisions that the POA&M tracks. An organization that maintains an impeccably formatted POA&M full of items that are never closed is not a well-managed security program — it is a well-documented one.

