## What I Am Still Thinking About

The 90-day aging review and the escalation process for items approaching deadlines — together, these create a governance cadence that makes the POA&M a genuine accountability instrument. But this cadence depends on the ISSO having the organizational standing to escalate without consequences.

In many healthcare organizations, the ISSO is not a senior organizational role. Escalating to the Executive Director about a Health IT Manager's missed POA&M deadline requires the ISSO to exercise authority that may not be clearly established in the organizational structure. If the ISSO lacks the organizational standing to escalate effectively — if their escalations are ignored, minimized, or create negative organizational dynamics — the POA&M accountability mechanism fails not because the ISSO is not trying, but because the organizational culture does not support security accountability at the governance level.

This is a GRC leadership challenge that frameworks do not address explicitly: the ISSO needs organizational backing from the AO and the Executive Director that makes escalation a normal part of the governance process rather than an exceptional action that requires the ISSO to choose between organizational harmony and security accountability.

The clearest solution is explicit AO backing in writing — an authorization condition or organizational charter that establishes the ISSO's authority to escalate POA&M deadline concerns to organizational leadership. If the AO has said, in writing, "the ISSO is authorized and expected to escalate unmet authorization commitments to senior leadership," the escalation is an organizational norm, not a political risk.

This is the kind of governance infrastructure that makes security programs sustainable — not just the technical controls and the RMF process, but the organizational authority structures that give the security function the standing to do its job.

